OverviewTo advance the state of IPv6 support across the consumer electronics ecosystem, CEA and major U.S. carriers are organizing an IPv6 interoperability test event. Participants will have the opportunity to test their dual-stack (IPv4/IPv6) and IPv6 capable devices and applications with the carriers, carrier-supplied routers and IP formats that are widely deployed to millions of broadband consumers today.
Further, manufacturers will have the opportunity to test their implementation to ensure they are compliant with the recently published CEA IPv6 device profiles standard, ANSI/CEA-2048.  For more information about the CEA IPv6 Device Profiles standard, see bit.ly/1vnkvCT.
UPnP Forum will be providing their IPv6 test tool for general use at the upcoming IPv6 interop event. John Berg from CableLabs will be there with a dedicated computer to run the test, but you may want to install the test tool on your own
title: CEA 2015 - IPv6 PlugFest

description:
The International Workshop on the Algorithmic Foundations of Robotics (WAFR) is a single-track workshop devoted to recent advances on algorithmic problems in robotics. The workshop proceedings will be published in a hardcover volume in the Springer STAR series, and selected papers will be invited for publication in a special issue of the International Journal of Robotics Research.
Topics
The focus of WAFR is on the design and analysis of robot algorithms from both theoretical and practical angles. The topics of interest are very broad. We encourage papers on fundamental algorithmic issues, such as complexity, completeness, machine learning, probabilistic reasoning, and new programming paradigms, to name a few. We also encourage papers on applications of robot algorithms to important or new domains, such as manufacturing, legged locomotion, distributed robotics, human-robot interaction, surgical robots, intelligent prosthetics, and brain-controlled robots. title: International Workshop on the Algorithmic Foundations of Robotics (WAFR)
